tation. The variously processed nuts were analyzed for the proximate and amino acid
compositions, and functional properties. The protein contents of the isolate ranges be-
tween 86.86 g/100g and 87.74 g/100 g, about 1.5- fold higher than those of the defat-
ted flour samples. The essential amino acids of the isolates ranged between
40.57%–41.55%. Glutamic acid, aspartic acid, and arginine were the most predominant
amino acids, while methionine and lysine were the first and second limiting amino acids,
respectively. The protein efficiency ratio, biological values as well as the functional
properties of the proteins were improved with processing. These properties may en-
